y) from Scotland in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Rankine","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Rankin  ."]},{"name":"Rand","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Rand</i>, a pet form of <i>Randolf</i>. Compare   Randolph  ,   Randall  ,   Randy  , and see also   Rance  .","English: habitational name from Rand (Lincolnshire), Rand Grange (North Yorkshire), or Raunds (Northamptonshire), all of which derive from Old English <i>rand</i> ‘edge, border, rim’.","German: from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic compound personal names formed with <i>rand</i> ‘rim (of a shield)’. Compare 1 above."]},{"name":"Rankins","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Rankin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Rank","meanings":["English: nickname for a powerfully built man or someone of violent emotions, from Middle English <i>rank</i> ‘proud, headstrong, stout-hearted’ (Old English <i>ranc</i> ‘proud, rebellious’).","English: from a Middle English personal name <i>Ranke</i>, a back-formation from the diminutive   Rankin  .","South German: variant of   Rang   2. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine)."]}]},{"name":"Reginald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Norman origin, derived from <i>Reginaldus</i>, a Latinized form of   Reynold   influenced by Latin <i>regina</i> ‘queen’. The full form is now regarded as very formal, and bearers generally shorten it to   Reg   in ordinary usage."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":19,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","